"# Chapter 16 — Safe introspection: perm, sandbox, and what shouldn't leak

Every chapter so far has been about what you can see. This chapter is about what you cannot — deliberately, honestly, by design.

Not all introspection is safe. Reading a verb's perm tier is safe. Reading a runtime secret environment variable is not. Reading a Cortex record you wrote is safe. Reading a stranger's cart's private state is not. Motoi's introspection surface draws the line and this chapter shows where.

## 16.1 The perm boundary

Every verb has a perm tier (Chapter 2). The dispatcher checks the caller's perm against the verb's requirement before allowing the call.

Introspection verbs are all `read` tier. That is deliberate — they only observe. But *what they observe* is bounded by what the runtime chooses to expose.

The registry snapshot returns metadata, not implementation. The metadata does not include the verb's actual function body, just its name, doc, contract, and pointer to source. If you want the body, you go read source; the runtime does not hand you the function.

Similarly, `snapshot-registry` returns a copy, not the live registry. Mutating the returned object does not affect the runtime's registry. This is a read-only projection.

## 16.2 Runtime redaction

A runtime can redact fields before returning them from introspection. Sensitive fields — source pointers pointing at proprietary code, doc strings referencing internal systems, examples exposing credentials — can be stripped.

```scheme
(source-of 'some-private-verb)
;; => nil    ;; runtime redacted the source pointer
```

The introspection layer is honest about the redaction — you get nil, not a fake pointer. If a field is nil where you expected a value, either the field was never populated or the runtime is redacting.

## 16.3 The never-introspectable mark

A cart author can mark specific values as never-introspectable. The runtime respects the mark — introspection verbs return an opaque placeholder.

```scheme
(define secret (make-opaque-value my-actual-secret))
(type-of secret)
;; => opaque

(shape-of secret)
;; => (:mechanical (:type opaque) :prose \"This value has been marked as never-introspectable by its creator.\")
```

The type is `opaque`. The mechanical fields are minimal. The LLM's prose is honest — the value cannot be introspected because someone said so.

