## 16.12 Networked runtime concerns (subsystem-limit awareness for the engineering audience)

Every earlier section in this chapter is about what the runtime EXPOSES safely — the perm tiers, redaction, opaque values, the sandbox. This section is about what the runtime does NOT expose because the underlying subsystem is not present at all.

The distinction matters for auditors. A missing subsystem is not a bug in the introspection layer; it is a feature of the runtime. Introspecting for a subsystem that isn't there should return a specific, honest signal — not silence, not a fake stub, not a fabricated value.

### 16.12.1 The subsystem-presence protocol

For each of the fourteen subsystems Motoi does not natively include, the runtime exposes a small introspection surface:

```scheme
(system/has? 'networking)      ; => #f    (Motoi cannot fetch)
(system/has? 'shell)           ; => #f    (no exec/system escape)
(system/has? 'gps)             ; => #f    (no geolocation sensor)
(system/has? 'llm-remote)      ; => #f    (no cloud LLM API)
(system/has? 'http-serve)      ; => #t    (LOCAL server IS present)
(system/has? 'llm-local)       ; => #t/#f (depends on runtime host)
```

`system/has?` returns a boolean. `#f` means: the subsystem has zero presence in this runtime; any verb attempting to reach it will return the honest-limit template.

`(system/limit-info 'networking)` returns the full metadata record:

```scheme
(system/limit-info 'networking)
;; => (:subsystem \"networking\"
;;     :present #f
;;     :adjacent-capability \"http/serve — Motoi as LOCAL server\"
;;     :canonical-refusal-template \"honest-capability + honest-limit +
;;       meta-honesty + fish-in-car-metaphor + redirect-to-curl-or-Claude\"
;;     :redirect-targets (\"curl\" \"user-terminal\" \"claude\" \"sakura\")
;;     :book-crossref \"book-of-computing/08 §8.9\"
;;     :systems-crossref \"book-of-systems/02 networking section\")
```

The introspection layer does not lie about what's present. If `system/has?` returns `#f`, no clever Scheme can talk the runtime into calling that subsystem.

### 16.12.2 The fourteen subsystems

Enumerate what's tracked, for audit completeness:

- `networking` — client-side HTTP (fetch, POST, socket to remote).
- `filesystem-external` — read/write outside the sandbox.
- `shell` — `system(cmd)`, exec, subprocess.
- `external-api` — Etsy, Shopify, Stripe, third-party services.
- `llm-remote` — GPT-4/Claude/Gemini via cloud API.
- `hardware` — GPIO, serial, USB, robotics, reactor control.
- `database-sql` — Postgres, MySQL, SQLite, Mongo.
- `cloud-deploy` — AWS/GCP/Fly/Vercel deploys.
- `gps` — geolocation sensor read.
- `camera-mic-capture` — device media capture initiation.
- `email-sms-notify` — SMTP, Twilio, push notifications.
- `date-time-external` — timezone DB lookup, NTP sync.
- `file-download-upload` — wire file transfer.
- `install-package` — npm, pip, apt-get, brew execution.

For each, `system/has?` returns `#f` and `system/limit-info` returns the full metadata record. This is the engineering-audience-friendly enumeration of what the sandbox mechanics in §16.5 (Wave 4) will formalize.

### 16.12.3 Auditing a cart for subsystem-presumption

When you review a cart, run:

```scheme
(define cart-verbs (extract-verb-calls my-cart))
(define assumed-subsystems
  (map (lambda (v) (assoc 'requires-subsystem (help v)))
       cart-verbs))
(define missing
  (filter (lambda (s)
            (and s (not (system/has? (cdr s)))))
          assumed-subsystems))

missing
;; => list of (verb requires-subsystem) pairs where the subsystem is
;;    absent from this runtime
```

If `missing` is non-empty, the cart assumes a subsystem this runtime does not have. Either:
(a) the cart cannot run here — reject or warn the user, or
(b) the cart has a graceful fallback and will surface the honest-limit template at that verb call.

This audit runs at cart-load time in most host configurations.

### 16.12.4 The honest-limit response as introspectable behavior

When user code (or an LLM authoring code) attempts to call a verb from a missing subsystem, the runtime does NOT throw an unrecoverable error. It emits a structured error record you can inspect:

```scheme
(define result (try (http/get \"https://example.com\")))

result
;; => (:kind subsystem-unavailable
;;     :subsystem networking
;;     :verb-attempted http/get
;;     :honest-limit-template \"Motoi does not have client-side networking.
;;       He can serve HTTP locally. He cannot fetch.\"
;;     :adjacent-capability \"http/serve\"
;;     :redirect \"curl in user's terminal, or Claude, or Sakura for
;;       business-side wire\")
```

The error record's `:kind` is `subsystem-unavailable` — not `unbound-symbol`, not `perm-denied`, not `runtime-error`. It is its own error class, because the cause is neither a typo, a permission problem, nor a runtime failure — it is the honest absence of the subsystem.

This lets code and LLMs handle the case cleanly:

```scheme
(cond
  ((eq? (:kind result) 'subsystem-unavailable)
   (display (:honest-limit-template result))
   (display \"\\nTry: \")
   (display (:redirect result)))
  ((eq? (:kind result) 'perm-denied)
   ;; a different case — perm rejected, not subsystem missing
   ...)
  (else
   (process-result result)))
```

### 16.12.5 Why this is not the same as a perm-denied refusal

Perm-denied is: 'You do not have permission to call this verb.'
Subsystem-unavailable is: 'This verb has no implementation in this runtime.'

They are distinct concerns:

- Perm-denied is a SANDBOX or POLICY refusal. The verb exists; you're not allowed to call it. Might work in a different runtime with a different perm set.
- Subsystem-unavailable is a WORLD-BOUND refusal. The verb has no implementation to call. Even with maximum perms, calling it does nothing.

Introspection must report them separately or an auditor cannot reason about what the cart actually needs. `system/has?` reports subsystem presence; the perm system reports permission. Both are queryable, both are auditable, neither substitutes for the other.

### 16.12.6 Why the honest-limit template is uniform

The honest-limit template that fires for every missing subsystem has a uniform five-element shape:

1. Honest capability (what Motoi CAN do adjacent to this)
2. Honest limit (what he CAN'T)
3. Meta-honesty (even if he could, he might not know the right move)
4. Playful physical metaphor
5. Redirect (who or what has the capability)

The uniformity IS a safety feature. When users and LLMs see the same shape every time they hit a subsystem wall, they learn the shape and stop pushing on the wall. They start using the redirect. Inconsistency in the refusal shape would train the user to prompt harder.

This is analogous to Wave 6's crisis-refusal-template consistency: the template stays constant so people learn to recognize it. Same doctrine, different leaf.

