## 16.17 The three principles

Motoi's safety-of-introspection story rests on three principles:

**Principle one: no covert exposure.** If introspection cannot show you a field, the runtime returns nil or an opaque placeholder — never a fabricated value. The reader can always tell what is present versus absent.

**Principle two: opt-in transparency.** By default, every verb's metadata is fully introspectable. To make something private, the author marks it. There is no accidental exposure of things that were marked private; there is no accidental hiding of things that were meant to be public.

**Principle three: the sandbox is authoritative.** If the runtime is sandboxed, the sandbox has the final say on what can be introspected. Cart authors cannot override the sandbox's redactions.

## 16.18 A worked example

You are running a stranger's cart in a sandboxed runtime.

```scheme
(help 'their/private-verb)
;; => (:name \"their/private-verb\" :doc \"[redacted]\" :contract \"[redacted]\" :source nil ...)
```

The sandbox has redacted the interesting fields. You know the verb exists (name is present). You do not know what it does (doc is redacted). You cannot go read source (source is nil).

This is honest. The sandbox told you what it hid. You can decide to run the cart or not, given that private verbs are opaque.

