## 16.21 The honesty principle, one more time

Every field the introspection layer returns is honest. If it says a verb exists, it exists. If it says a field is nil, the field is nil. If it says a value is opaque, the value is opaque. There are no false negatives, no false positives, no misleading returns.

This is what makes introspection trustworthy. If you cannot trust the returns, the whole surface collapses. Motoi trades some flexibility for that trust — the runtime cannot silently expose secrets and cannot silently hide things — and the trade is worth it for a language that wants to be introspected freely.

## 16.22 A closing observation

Introspection and safety compose the same way every other pair in this book composes. Small primitives. Uniform metadata. Explicit fields. The safety story is not a separate system; it is the same introspection layer, with a few extra fields (`:redacted`, `:opaque`, `:confidentiality`) that mean something specific.

Learn to read those fields the same way you learned to read the doc field. When you see nil where a value was expected, ask why. Sometimes the field was never populated. Sometimes the runtime redacted. Sometimes the value is opaque by design. All three are honest returns; you just have to know which is which.

## 16.23 The book closes

Sixteen chapters. Every question you can ask about a Motoi program has a verb that will answer it — unless the answer would leak something the runtime chose to protect, in which case the runtime tells you honestly that the answer is unavailable.

That is the whole introspection surface.

Turn to the appendices for reference material, cheat sheets, and worked examples of the patterns from throughout the book.

## 16.24 Deep-seed — the sandbox model

Motoi's dispatcher (`src/dispatch.js`) checks every verb call against the caller's perm tier. If the caller does not have the required perm, the call errors with `perm-denied`.

The sandbox is stricter — it can also add allow-lists (only these specific verbs) and deny-lists (never these), regardless of perm.

Introspection verbs are all `read` tier. In most sandboxes they are allowed. But a paranoid sandbox can deny even introspection — for example, refusing `snapshot-registry` if it does not want the cart to enumerate the whole verb space.

If introspection is denied, the introspection verbs error like any other perm-denied verb. The error record's `:kind` is `perm-denied`. You can catch it and adjust behavior.

## 16.25 Deep-seed — Cortex confidentiality

Cortex records can carry a `:confidentiality` field:

```scheme
(cortex/record
  :subject 'user
  :predicate 'ssn
  :object \"123-45-6789\"
  :at (current-second)
  :source 'user-input
  :confidentiality 'personal-data)
```

When another verb queries Cortex, the runtime checks the querier's perm against the record's confidentiality. If the querier does not have `personal-data` perm, the record is filtered out.

This means introspection over Cortex is also perm-gated. `cortex/query` respects confidentiality. You do not accidentally expose personal data by listing every record about a user.

## 16.26 Deep-seed — the audit pattern

If you are running a cart and want to know what it introspected during a session, you can trace the introspection verbs themselves:

```scheme
(,trace help)
(,trace snapshot-registry)
(,trace cortex/query)

(run-the-cart)

(,trace-log help)
;; every help call the cart made
```

Now you know exactly what the cart looked at. If it snooped your Cortex records unnecessarily, or introspected verbs it should not have needed, the log tells you.

This is defense-in-depth. Perm-gating stops the cart from calling verbs it should not; tracing tells you what it did call. Together they give you visibility into introspection-as-surveillance.

Turn to the appendices.

